-- British Airways, Ferrovial, PPR, Sanofi: Europe Equity Preview
-- B y   T a r a   L a c h a p e l l e
-- 2010-10-29T04:00:01Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-28/european-stocks-gain-as-eni-france-telecom-dassault-top-profit-estimates.html
The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in  European  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are from the previous close.  The  Stoxx Europe 600 Index  advanced 0.4 percent to 265.90.
The  Stoxx 50 Index  rose 0.5 percent to 2,543.14. The  Euro Stoxx
50 Index , a benchmark for nations using the euro, gained 0.6
percent to 2,845.53.  Banco Popular Espanol SA  (POP SM): The Spanish lender will
probably say third-quarter profit fell to about 141 million
euros from 209 million euros a year earlier, according to the
average analyst estimate in a Bloomberg survey. The shares
slipped 0.9 percent to 4.58 euros.  Belgacom SA  (BELG BB): The largest telephone company in
Belgium may say third-quarter earnings before interest, tax,
depreciation and amortization declined to 490.2 million euros,
the average of 14 analyst  estimates  compiled by Bloomberg, from
494 million euros a year earlier. Belgacom advanced 0.9 percent
to 28.40 euros.  British Airways Plc  (BAY LN): The U.K. carrier is scheduled
to report earnings. Net income may reach 164.8 million pounds
($263 million) in the three months ended Sept. 30 from a year-
earlier loss, the average estimate of five analysts compiled by
Bloomberg shows. The shares advanced 1 percent to 280.7 pence.  Exmar NV  (EXM BB): The operator of the world’s largest
fleet of midsize gas tankers said third-quarter earnings before
interest and taxes rose to $10 million from $9.8 million a year
earlier and aims to complete the sale of 50 percent stakes in
two liquefied-natural-gas carriers to Teekay LNG Partners LP in
the current quarter. Exmar declined 0.6 percent to 5.47 euros.  Ferrovial SA  (FER SM): The manager of airports and highways
posted a nine-month profit of 315 million euros, compared with a
loss of 191 million euros a year earlier. Sales grew 0.3 percent
to 9.1 billion euros. The company will pay a 2010 interim
dividend of 12 euro cents per share next month. The stock fell
0.1 percent to 7.93 euros.  Next Plc  (NXT LN): The U.K.’s second-largest clothing
retailer was raised to “Hold” from “Sell” at Societe
Generale. The shares advanced 0.5 percent to 2,284 pence.  PPR SA  (PP FP): The owner of the Bottega Veneta luxury
brand said third-quarter sales rose 13 percent, beating
analysts’ estimates, on increased demand for fashion and leather
goods in Asia. The shares rose 0.7 percent to 118.55 euros.  Sanofi-Aventis SA  (SAN FP): The drugmaker said it will
acquire BMP Sunstone, the maker of the Hao Wa Wa brand of
children’s cough and cold treatments, for $520.6 million. The
shares rose 0.3 percent to 49.70 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
